\section{Classes for representing corpora}
% ----------------------------------------------------------------
% ----------------------------------------------------------------
\label{sec:classes}

There are four classes for representing a corpus. Each may be more
suited for a given task or for a given source. Functions allow
conversion between them.

\subsection{\texttt{fullText}}
\label{subsec:classes-fullText}

The \texttt{fullText} class is the more simplistic representation of
a corpus: it is a list whose elements are vectors containing tokens.

It may be usefull for reading any file containing text and tokenizing it.  The
function \texttt{lines2fullText} receive a filename in argument; each line is
tokenized separatly and give an element of the list.

\texttt{summary} and \texttt{print} functions pretty print a fullText corpus.

<<fullText, echo=TRUE>>=
library(lexicalStat);
fileName <- system.file(c("exempleData"),
                        "LeMondeEco.small.lines",
                        package="lexicalStat")
c <- lines2fullText(fileName);
summary(c);
print(c);
@

