\subsection{\texttt{tabulated}}
\label{subsec:classes-tabulated}

A tabulated corpus is a more rich representation:
\begin{itemize}
\item several features can be represented for each token (such as inflected form, lemma and pos) and not only one feature as in \texttt{fullText}). 
\item several partition of the corpus can be represented, and not only one as in \texttt{fullText} (the repartition of tokens between list slot).
\end{itemize}

This representation is inspired by the representation found in the \texttt{CWB}\index{CWB} corpus software.

A common use of this data structure is for representing tabulated data produced
by part-of-speech tagger. A function allows for reading treetagger output file.
XML tag are interpreted as 

<<tabulated, echo=TRUE>>=
  fileName <- system.file(c("inst", "exempleData"), "sample.ttg", package="lexicalStat")
  tabulated <- read.treetagger(fileName);
  summary(tabulated);
  print(tabulated);
@

\subsection{\texttt{lexicalTable}}
\label{subsec:classes-lexicalTable}

A lexical table is a contingency table where rows are the given forms found in
the corpus, and columns the differents parts of the corpus.

LexicalTable object are reprensented using sparse matrix (from the package
\texttt{Matrix}). They can be read from files or created thanks to data.frame,
matrix, or other corpus representations such as \texttt{fullText} or
\texttt{tabulated}.

<<tabulated, echo=TRUE>>=
  base <- paste(system.file(package = "lexicalStat"), "exempleData", "lemonde.lemme", sep="/")
  x <- readLexicalTable(base);
  summary(x);
  print(x);
@

\subsection{\texttt{frequencyList}}
\label{subsec:classes-frequencyList}

A frequencyList is a simple named vector of total frequency.

